00:04:58.870 --> 00:05:01.310
So obviously it's a
real honor to be here.

00:05:01.310 --> 00:05:05.150
It's exciting to be in Washington
D.C. at this time of year,

00:05:05.150 --> 00:05:07.790
and on this special
weekend, and I thank you

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:10.760
so much for coming to see me.

00:05:10.760 --> 00:05:14.490
So I'm going to tell you a little
bit about sort of, my journey,

00:05:14.490 --> 00:05:18.050
and how I came to be
standing here, and then yes,

00:05:18.050 --> 00:05:23.050 position:56%
I would love to answer any questions
from any of you that you would like.

00:05:23.050 --> 00:05:24.940
And frankly, I'm really
interested in the questions

00:05:24.940 --> 00:05:27.410
that you would've asked
if we weren't filming,

00:05:27.410 --> 00:05:30.740
but I guess I don't get that, so.

00:05:30.740 --> 00:05:35.580
I'm not one of those
people who always thought

00:05:35.580 --> 00:05:37.600
that they would be a writer.

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:41.890
In fact I would have said that
writing was a job for dreamers

00:05:41.890 --> 00:05:45.020
and I'm not much of a dreamer.

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:49.730
The way it sort of came to me,
was when I was in my third year

00:05:49.730 --> 00:05:53.830
of law school, I was, I don't
know maybe 24 years old,

00:05:53.830 --> 00:05:55.690
I don't know how old I was then.

00:05:55.690 --> 00:06:00.520
Young. My mother was
dying of breast cancer.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:04.680
And so every day after
class I would you know,

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:09.070
go hang out in her hospital room,
and I'm sure a lot of you have been

00:06:09.070 --> 00:06:13.820
in these situations, and you know
that there are just a lot of things

00:06:13.820 --> 00:06:18.800
that you don't want to talk about,
or you aren't ready to talk about,

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:23.720 position:56%
and I was there one day, and because
I was young and because I was

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:27.820
in school, I was complaining
about my classes.

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:32.340
I had signed up for a
corporate tax, which for a girl

00:06:32.340 --> 00:06:34.600
who can't add, is a very bad idea.

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:38.680
And I was complaining to my
mother that I was not doing well

00:06:38.680 --> 00:06:41.190
in the class, and she said,

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:45.590
well don't worry you're
going to be a writer anyway.

00:06:45.590 --> 00:06:49.530
And of course, my dad's in the
back going, we just got her

00:06:49.530 --> 00:06:52.560
into law school, you know.

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:56.030
And my thought is, somebody
needs to check her morphine drip

00:06:56.030 --> 00:06:58.880
because this makes no sense at all.

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:02.510
I had never written
a word of fiction.

00:07:02.510 --> 00:07:08.030
But, I think you know, I didn't
want to think about, at that point,

00:07:08.030 --> 00:07:11.820
all of the heaviness that was
coming, that she wouldn't be

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:15.510
at my wedding, that she wouldn't
be there when I had my first child,

00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:19.210 position:56%
that we didn't have a life together.

00:07:19.210 --> 00:07:24.480
And so she said, you know I think
we should write a book together.

00:07:24.480 --> 00:07:26.190
And I jumped on this opportunity.

00:07:26.190 --> 00:07:28.550
I said definitely, let's do that.

00:07:28.550 --> 00:07:33.180
So being mother and daughter, we
immediately locked into battle

00:07:33.180 --> 00:07:36.630
about what kind of
book we should write.

00:07:36.630 --> 00:07:41.920
I wanted to write horror and she
wanted to write historical romance.

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:45.820
So, now today you could
do those together,

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:48.990
but not so much in the late 80s.

00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:51.290
And so, you know, we
kind of battled,

00:07:51.290 --> 00:07:54.310
and ultimately my mom said
look, I'm sick, I win,

00:07:54.310 --> 00:07:56.850
we're writing historical romance.

00:07:56.850 --> 00:07:58.150
And so I said okay.

00:07:58.150 --> 00:08:03.420
So this was you know,
the pre-internet era,

00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:06.230
so that meant going to the
library every single day,

00:08:06.230 --> 00:08:10.280
standing in the dusty stacks
of Suzzallo at the University

00:08:10.280 --> 00:08:13.380
of Washington and just
xeroxing pages

00:08:13.380 --> 00:08:16.170
and pages and pages of material.

00:08:16.170 --> 00:08:20.590
And I would bring all of my
material back to her hospital room

00:08:20.590 --> 00:08:23.630
and we would talk about, you
know, we could spend a whole day

00:08:23.630 --> 00:08:27.090
on what did her dress look like,
what did her shoes look like,

00:08:27.090 --> 00:08:31.360
and just collected all this
research, plotted this book,

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:36.090
which by the way, we thought
was a revolutionary idea,

00:08:36.090 --> 00:08:43.570 position:56%
about a woman who dresses as a cabin
boy and sneaks onto a pirate ship.

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:50.380
And so we did all this research
and I actually, in 1986,

00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:54.350
I wrote my very first words of
fiction, I wrote Chapter One,

00:08:54.350 --> 00:08:58.500
I wrote a scene, and I hadn't
even finished the scene

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:01.070
when I got the call from
my dad saying you need

00:09:01.070 --> 00:09:02.870
to come to the hospital.

00:09:02.870 --> 00:09:07.860
So I was able to sort of whisper
in my mother's ear, I started.

00:09:07.860 --> 00:09:12.060
But she was never able to
read anything, unfortunately.

00:09:12.060 --> 00:09:16.150
And so, after she passed
away I really had no interest

00:09:16.150 --> 00:09:17.790
in being a writer.

00:09:17.790 --> 00:09:19.700
I was a lawyer.

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:25.110 position:56%
And so I finished law school and you
know, went back with ordinary life,

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:31.010
packed up everything into this
box, and put it into my closet.

00:09:31.010 --> 00:09:35.710
And several years later, when
I got pregnant with my son,

00:09:35.710 --> 00:09:39.130
I went into labor at 14 weeks.

00:09:39.130 --> 00:09:42.990 position:56%
And that's when I realized I wasn't
going to have an ordinary pregnancy,

00:09:42.990 --> 00:09:45.870
and I knew, you know, that
I wasn't going to be able

00:09:45.870 --> 00:09:50.760 position:56%
to have any more kids, and I would
be very lucky to keep the one I had,

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:55.070
and I was in bed for
the entire pregnancy.

00:09:55.070 --> 00:09:59.040
&gt;&gt; This was 1987, I guess.

00:09:59.040 --> 00:10:03.710
So of course all my girlfriends
are working, my husband is working,

00:10:03.710 --> 00:10:05.950
there is no good day time TV.

00:10:05.950 --> 00:10:11.660
For those of you old enough to
remember, Erica Kane was bedridden

00:10:11.660 --> 00:10:15.720
with Bianca at the exact same time.

00:10:15.720 --> 00:10:17.700
Bianca's now like 60.

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:21.520
But so I tried watching
All My Children

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:24.140
and Erica was just not having
the same bedridden pregnancy

00:10:24.140 --> 00:10:27.600
that I was, so I turned off the TV.

00:10:27.600 --> 00:10:32.580
And then I tried The Price is
Right, but when you start yelling

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:35.270
out refrigerator prices
to an empty room,

00:10:35.270 --> 00:10:38.340
you know that you need
to do something fast.

00:10:38.340 --> 00:10:42.360
And I think at some point in there
my husband sort of poked his head

00:10:42.360 --> 00:10:45.230
in the room, well what
about that book that you

00:10:45.230 --> 00:10:47.490
and Sharon were going to write?

00:10:47.490 --> 00:10:50.700
And I thought, oh that's right, the
book that we were going to write.

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:54.780
So I pulled down this box, and
here's this gift from my mom,

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:56.630
of all of this research
and everything

00:10:56.630 --> 00:10:59.100
that you need to write a book.

00:10:59.100 --> 00:11:00.940
And I thought, how hard can it be?

00:11:00.940 --> 00:11:02.240
I can do this.

00:11:02.240 --> 00:11:04.420
I've got like seven months.

00:11:04.420 --> 00:11:09.390
And you know, so I learned to boot
up a computer and I got out all

00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:13.730
of these things and I started
writing, and you know what?

00:11:13.730 --> 00:11:15.320
It wasn't hard.

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:22.910
In fact, I was so talented,
like right from the start,

00:11:22.910 --> 00:11:25.210
that I didn't need to edit.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:29.640
I didn't need to change a word,

00:11:29.640 --> 00:11:33.050
it just came out perfectly
the first time.

00:11:33.050 --> 00:11:39.400
So I wrote this entire historical
romance novel, unedited, unchanged,

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:43.550
in one pass, and then
I thought, okay,

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:48.190
what lucky agent should
I send this to?

00:11:48.190 --> 00:11:52.990
And I did all my lawyer research,
you know, and I sent it off,

00:11:52.990 --> 00:11:57.210
and I sent it off I think about
a week before I had my son.

00:11:57.210 --> 00:12:00.460
And then I started
dreaming of book tours,

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:04.650
and how I would handle
multiple offers from publishers,

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:07.460
and you know, waiting
for all of that stuff.

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:12.380
And ultimately, I heard
back from the agent,

00:12:12.380 --> 00:12:17.260
and she said you may have
talent, frankly how could I tell?

00:12:17.260 --> 00:12:23.340
And I thought, wait a
minute, it's going to be hard?

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:27.820
You know, I really, honestly I
was young and I didn't understand.

00:12:27.820 --> 00:12:30.290
I had made the decision
to be a writer.

00:12:30.290 --> 00:12:31.930
I had written a book.

00:12:31.930 --> 00:12:35.390 position:56%
That seemed like what was necessary.

00:12:35.390 --> 00:12:38.360
And that was when I
really understood

00:12:38.360 --> 00:12:44.260
that writing was unlike anything
else I had undertaken in my life.

00:12:44.260 --> 00:12:50.260
And that I would have to sort
of embrace the concept of effort

00:12:50.260 --> 00:12:56.140 position:56%
and failure and uncertainty, and I
would have to try to learn something

00:12:56.140 --> 00:13:00.470
that you almost have
to learn internally.

00:13:00.470 --> 00:13:04.890
And I thought, well, okay, I'm
going to give myself five years.

00:13:04.890 --> 00:13:06.870
I'm going to try to do this.

00:13:06.870 --> 00:13:13.960
I mean always go back to the law if
I have to, and so I undertook sort

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:18.160
of this, journey, of
beginning to write.

00:13:18.160 --> 00:13:21.900
Because I had a young son, I
couldn't go take a lot of classes,

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:24.890
I couldn't do a lot of
things, so I had to you know,

00:13:24.890 --> 00:13:28.310
do it sort of, as best I could.

00:13:28.310 --> 00:13:34.150
And one of the first things I
did, was I went to a conference,

00:13:34.150 --> 00:13:39.520
not unlike this, but smaller than
this, but it was some authors

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:41.480 position:56%
that were speaking about their work.

00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:46.250 position:56%
I remember walking into the room,
there was maybe 100 people in there,

00:13:46.250 --> 00:13:50.390
and what I remember
was they were so old.

00:13:50.390 --> 00:13:52.710
They were at least 40.

00:13:53.960 --> 00:13:57.540
And I thought I just don't belong
here, I don't know what to do.

00:13:57.540 --> 00:13:59.400
So I did what I always
do which is race

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:01.910
to the restroom to collect myself.

00:14:01.910 --> 00:14:04.410
I was about 29 at this point.

00:14:04.410 --> 00:14:08.660 position:56%
And there was another woman standing
in there who was my same age,

00:14:08.660 --> 00:14:14.670
who was also hiding out from the
old people at the conference.

00:14:14.670 --> 00:14:18.400
And we still how it
happened, but we decided

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:20.170
to start critiquing each other.

00:14:20.170 --> 00:14:23.790
So we said, we traded
books, I read hers

00:14:23.790 --> 00:14:27.530
and I went oh man,
you are so talented.

00:14:27.530 --> 00:14:30.520
And she read me, you, too.

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:35.040
And so we just started,
you know, working,

00:14:35.040 --> 00:14:37.910
and she was a TV news
producer, I was a lawyer

00:14:37.910 --> 00:14:41.310
so we had this really
strong work ethic.

00:14:41.310 --> 00:14:46.700
And we just never took
no, we never gave up.

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:51.150
My dad, you know, kept thinking,
so you're still writing,

00:14:51.150 --> 00:14:55.180
I thought macrame would be next,
then paint by numbers, you know,

00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:57.940
but we just sort of
kept working at it.

00:14:57.940 --> 00:15:05.620
And I was fortunate enough to sell
my first book when my son was two.

00:15:05.620 --> 00:15:11.710
And so I just kind of, you
know, moved into this wonderful,

00:15:11.710 --> 00:15:16.710
wonderful job, which was a
novelist and an at home mom,

00:15:16.710 --> 00:15:25.050 position:56%
who was able to go to every you
know, field trip, party, everything,

00:15:25.050 --> 00:15:30.350 position:56%
until my son said, you know, for the
love of God, stop coming to school,

00:15:30.350 --> 00:15:33.220
I can't stand it anymore.

00:15:34.510 --> 00:15:39.910 position:56%
And in what has become a pattern
for me, I seemed to have about a six

00:15:39.910 --> 00:15:43.700
or seven year attention span.

00:15:43.700 --> 00:15:49.090
And so I did, I worked, I wrote
romances for about six years,

00:15:49.090 --> 00:15:52.860
and then I started
to feel constrained.

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:56.280
I started to feel like I wanted
to tell different stories.

00:15:56.280 --> 00:15:58.650
I wanted to tell them
in a different way.

00:15:58.650 --> 00:16:06.550
I wanted to focus on prose and
relationships of all kinds.

00:16:06.550 --> 00:16:12.560
And so I said to my agent, I'm
going to write a hard cover novel.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:15.180
And she said, oh no,
that doesn't happen.

00:16:15.180 --> 00:16:17.440
You can't go from romance you know.

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:20.070
And so I said, yeah I think I can.

00:16:20.070 --> 00:16:24.600
And I wrote my first hard cover,

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:26.890
what they now call
women's fiction novel,

00:16:26.890 --> 00:16:31.370
in about 1998 or something I think.

00:16:31.370 --> 00:16:36.110
And did that for a long time,
about six years actually.

00:16:36.110 --> 00:16:38.070
Loved it. Had a great time.

00:16:38.070 --> 00:16:40.450
And about six years after
that I started to feel

00:16:40.450 --> 00:16:43.860
that I had this story to tell.

00:16:43.860 --> 00:16:46.010
But I wasn't exactly
sure what it was.

00:16:46.010 --> 00:16:51.600
I just knew it was a story about
my generation, about girls, women,

00:16:51.600 --> 00:16:56.810
