00:33:38.480 --> 00:33:43.360
and was sensitive in a way that we
haven't really read about before?

00:33:43.360 --> 00:33:44.660
&gt;&gt; Kristin Hannah: Yes.

00:33:44.660 --> 00:33:47.890
The easy answer is that
was very challenging.

00:33:47.890 --> 00:33:51.530
And it was something that gave me
a lot of pause, and I gave a lot

00:33:51.530 --> 00:33:54.260
of thought to how I
wanted to do this.

00:33:54.260 --> 00:34:00.320
But the bottom line was my goal
in writing The Nightingale,

00:34:00.320 --> 00:34:02.900
and what I thought, the
reason that I finally jumped

00:34:02.900 --> 00:34:05.070
and said okay I'm going
to write this story,

00:34:05.070 --> 00:34:09.880
was because what I
think my skill set is

00:34:09.880 --> 00:34:14.400
as a writer, is emotional impact.

00:34:14.400 --> 00:34:17.870
My job is to make you actually
feel it, not just read the words,

00:34:17.870 --> 00:34:21.440
not just understand what's
going on, but actually feel it.

00:34:21.440 --> 00:34:30.720
And the idea of the bad
Nazi was so easy to do.

00:34:30.720 --> 00:34:32.940
And it felt like it had
been done so many times.

00:34:32.940 --> 00:34:36.460
And so I wanted to
explore something,

00:34:36.460 --> 00:34:40.000
a man with a little bit
more shading than that.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:45.710
And sort of imply that he was
caught up in this in the same way

00:34:45.710 --> 00:34:51.020
that the sisters were
and you know, that,

00:34:51.020 --> 00:34:54.100
just humanize him I
guess is the best answer.

00:34:54.100 --> 00:34:57.260
And actually I'm really
glad that I did that.

00:34:57.260 --> 00:35:01.540
I think it actually gave
a resonance to the book.

00:35:01.540 --> 00:35:02.920
And I'm glad your book
club liked it.

00:35:02.920 --> 00:35:04.220
&gt;&gt; We loved it.

00:35:04.220 --> 00:35:06.710
&gt;&gt; Kristin Hannah:
Thanks for picking it.

00:35:06.710 --> 00:35:11.190
&gt;&gt; Hi. I'm in a book group also,
and the first book of yours

00:35:11.190 --> 00:35:12.980
that we chose was In
The Winter Garden,

00:35:12.980 --> 00:35:15.270
which is the first book
of yours I ever read.

00:35:15.270 --> 00:35:18.100
I really loved it and then
I listened to it on tape,

00:35:18.100 --> 00:35:21.070
and tears going down my face.

00:35:21.070 --> 00:35:24.430
So and it really resonated
with me the whole,

00:35:24.430 --> 00:35:29.720
siege and eating wall
paper paste and everything.

00:35:29.720 --> 00:35:31.020
I still think about it.

00:35:31.020 --> 00:35:34.430
So I wanted to ask you, how
did you do research for that?

00:35:34.430 --> 00:35:36.830
How did you find out
about these things?

00:35:36.830 --> 00:35:38.290
Did it really happen?

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:40.470
And did you go to Russia?

00:35:40.470 --> 00:35:41.770
&gt;&gt; Kristin Hannah: No
I didn't go to Russia.

00:35:41.770 --> 00:35:43.070
I would so like to.

00:35:43.070 --> 00:35:45.410
She's asking about Winter Garden
if you can't hear back there,

00:35:45.410 --> 00:35:47.220
and how I did the research.

00:35:47.220 --> 00:35:50.380
You know, it's interesting having
done now two World War II books

00:35:50.380 --> 00:35:56.570
about women, trying to
survive in difficult times,

00:35:56.570 --> 00:36:02.290
in the French research, there's
a lot of research about the women

00:36:02.290 --> 00:36:07.020
who did the cool stuff, like
the couriers, the spies,

00:36:07.020 --> 00:36:10.310
the downed airman over the
Pyrenees, or you know those roots.

00:36:10.310 --> 00:36:14.600
There's a lot of really good
memoir material about that.

00:36:14.600 --> 00:36:20.660
About the women who saved
Jewish children, very little.

00:36:20.660 --> 00:36:24.910 position:56%
And about the women who survived
The Siege of Leningrad, very little.

00:36:24.910 --> 00:36:27.910
Because Stalin kept a
lid on it for so long,

00:36:27.910 --> 00:36:31.290
so a lot of those stories
are you know, coming out now.

00:36:31.290 --> 00:36:36.930 position:56%
But it was really, you know, trying
to find the few memoirs that existed

00:36:36.930 --> 00:36:39.200
and you know, try to
talk to survivors,

00:36:39.200 --> 00:36:42.880
but it was very difficult, you
know, in World War II Russia.

00:36:42.880 --> 00:36:44.510
But that was the book
that made me believe

00:36:44.510 --> 00:36:46.550
that The Nightingale was possible,

00:36:46.550 --> 00:36:50.720
so I have a very warm
feeling for that book still.

00:36:50.720 --> 00:36:53.970
I think I'm done?

00:36:53.970 --> 00:36:56.150
Okay. Oh. One more.

00:36:56.150 --> 00:36:57.450
Last question.

00:36:57.450 --> 00:36:58.860
&gt;&gt; I also have question
about Winter Garden.

00:36:58.860 --> 00:37:04.070
What gave you the idea to
go into that specific topic?

00:37:04.070 --> 00:37:07.550
&gt;&gt; Kristin Hannah: Well for any of
you who have seen The Descendants,

00:37:07.550 --> 00:37:12.910
which seems like a non sequitur,
but there's a little bar in Kauai,

00:37:12.910 --> 00:37:16.230
called The Tahiti Nui, that's been
there since the 60s and that's

00:37:16.230 --> 00:37:18.180
where it was in the movie.

00:37:18.180 --> 00:37:21.340
I was sitting with a girlfriend
and we're having a Mai Tai,

00:37:21.340 --> 00:37:26.550
everybody's shoulder to shoulder,
and I was saying to my girlfriend,

00:37:26.550 --> 00:37:29.900
this was right after Firefly Lane,
I said I want to write a book

00:37:29.900 --> 00:37:34.810
about how amazing we women
are to protect our kids,

00:37:34.810 --> 00:37:38.260
how we can like move a truck,
you know, to save their lives.

00:37:38.260 --> 00:37:40.930
And my girlfriend says yeah
well good luck with that,

00:37:40.930 --> 00:37:44.670
and the guy sitting next to me says
well you know, if you're interested

00:37:44.670 --> 00:37:47.730
in strong women, you
should check the Siege

00:37:47.730 --> 00:37:50.090
of Leningrad, World War II.

00:37:50.090 --> 00:37:52.570
And first thought was how long
have you been listening to us?

00:37:52.570 --> 00:37:56.120 position:56%
And what have we been talking about?

00:37:56.120 --> 00:37:59.600
But it turns out he was a
pilot and he just sent me

00:37:59.600 --> 00:38:02.920
to World War II Russia, and when
I found the story of the Siege

00:38:02.920 --> 00:38:05.070
of Leningrad, my heart
was so broken.

00:38:05.070 --> 00:38:09.170
And again, it's a lost story.

00:38:09.170 --> 00:38:12.550
You know, I mean, it became,
they called it a city of women

00:38:12.550 --> 00:38:15.250
because the men were all gone
and you know, they were starving

00:38:15.250 --> 00:38:18.560
in there, and again I just
wanted this story told

00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:21.170
because I thought it was amazing.

00:38:21.170 --> 00:38:22.970
Thank you.

